  "prompt": "I have sodium bicarbonate, how can I know if is it true?",
  "response": "To test whether what you have is sodium bicarbonate (baking soda), you can perform a simple test:\n\n### Visual and Textural Examination\n1. **Appearance**: Sodium bicarbonate is typically a white, fine powder. \n2. **Texture**: When you feel it between your fingers, it should feel gritty but can also be somewhat soft.\n\n### Solubility Test\n1. **Mix with Water**: Dissolve a small amount (about a teaspoon) of the powder in water.\n2. **Reaction**: Sodium bicarbonate is soluble in water, so it should dissolve relatively easily. \n\n### Acid Reaction Test\nSodium bicarbonate reacts with acids to produce carbon dioxide, which causes fizzing.\n\n1. **Vinegar Test**: \n   - Take a small amount of your powder and place it in a bowl or container.\n   - Pour a small amount of vinegar (acetic acid) over it.\n   - Observe if it fizzes. If it produces bubbles and fizzes, then it is likely that you have sodium bicarbonate.\n\n### pH Test\nIf you have access to pH strips or a pH meter:\n1. Dissolve a small amount of the powder in water.\n2. Measure the pH. Sodium bicarbonate should produce a solution with a pH around 8-9, which indicates it is basic.\n\n### Note\nIf you have any doubts about the purity or safety of the substance, consult a chemist or consider purchasing a new batch from a reliable source. Always take care to perform tests in a safe environment.",
